          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search           Triumph of the Human Spirit   The sculpture at Foley Square in 2008    Artist Lorenzo Pace   Year 2000 (2000)   Type Sculpture   Material Black granite   Location New York City, New York, United States   Coordinates 40°42′52″N 74°00′10″W﻿ / ﻿40.71445°N 74.00289°W﻿ / 40.71445; -74.00289Coordinates: 40°42′52″N 74°00′10″W﻿ / ﻿40.71445°N 74.00289°W﻿ / 40.71445; -74.00289   Triumph of the Human Spirit is an outdoor 2000 black granite sculpture by Lorenzo Pace, installed at Foley Square in Manhattan, New York, United States. According to the City of New York, the abstract monument is derived from the antelope forms of Bambaran art. The sculpture is sited near a Colonial-era African-American burial ground, and its support structure alludes to the slave trade's Middle Passage.[1] See also[edit]  2000 in art African Burial Ground National Monument, Lower Manhattan  References[edit]   ^ "Honoring the African-American Experience: Triumph of the Human Spirit". The City of New York. Retrieved August 2, 2015.                       Retrieved from "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Triumph_of_the_Human_Spirit&oldid=684889083"          Categories: 2000 establishments in New York2000 sculpturesAbstract sculptures in New YorkAfrican-American history in New York CityCivic Center, ManhattanGranite sculptures in New YorkMonuments and memorials in New YorkOutdoor sculptures in New York CityHidden categories: Coordinates not on Wikidata            
